Description of the data

The survey data contains information about approaches and study skills, and attitudes toward statistics.For this exercie, 166 observations of 7 variables are extracted from the ASSIST (Approaches and Study Skills Inventory for Students) and SATS (Survey of Attitudes Toward Statistics) data sources. The variables considered for the survey are age, attitude towards statistics, gender, exam points,and study approaches(deep, startegic and surface).

As can be seen from the graph, the data distribution shows an increasing trend and there exists some relationship between attitude and exam point. The relationship is positive and linear, i.e. as the attitude gets better, students results increase. In general, the relation tells us that those students having a good attitude towards statics tend to score good results. `

model=lm(Points~Attitude+Age+stra, data=df)
summary(model)

## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 10.89543    2.64834   4.114 6.17e-05 ***
## Attitude     0.34808    0.05622   6.191 4.72e-09 ***
## Age         -0.08822    0.05302  -1.664   0.0981 .  
## stra         1.00371    0.53434   1.878   0.0621 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.26 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2182, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2037 
## F-statistic: 15.07 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 1.07e-08

The regression result (Points = 0.34808xAttitude - 0.08822xAge + 1.00371xStra) show that exam points are related positively to attitude and strategic study approach, while negatively to age. However, summeries of the statistics indicates that only attitude has significant or statistically meaningful relations with exam points, with three star(0.001) showing significant value. For a dependent variable to be statistically significant, p value should be less than or equal to 0.05.Hence age and strategic approach will be removed and the model fit will be run again. Moreover, attitude has a higher t value, meaning it is far by more than six standard deviations from zero and possible to reject the null hypothesis, i.e. we can declare a relationship between Points and Attitude. In addition the standard error is low(round 0.05), meaning the model varies only by 0.05 incase we ran it again and again.

model=lm(Points~Attitude, data=df)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ Attitude, data = df)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 11.63715    1.83035   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## Attitude     0.35255    0.05674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

The model indicates that for a unit increase in attitude value, the exam points will increase by 0.35 and the relationship is significant. The residul standard error on the other hand shows, how much the model prediction deviates from the actual value, i.e. the exam points can deviate by 5.32 points from the actual value. The F-statistics(38.6) is larger than 1 and thus indicates there is a relationship between value and attitude, and the it’s enough to reject the null hypothesis. The multiple r-squared measure how well the model is fitting the actual data. Meaning, around only 19%(r=0.19) of the variance in the response variable(points) is explained by the predictor varible(attitude). And thus the model has low performance.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model,1)
plot(model,2)
plot(model,5)

The normal Q-Q plot shows that the residuals lined up at 45°compared to an ideal normal observations and hence normality assumption of the linear regression holds true. The residuals vs Fitted graph helps to check if the linearity assumption is true. The closer the line to zero,the better the model in meeting linearity assumptions. The residuals, in this case, shows values beyond 2 and -2 standard deviation and thus the linearity assumption needs to be checked. The residual vs leverage result displayed that there is no influential attitude data that can change the slope of the regression model.

The data set comprised of 382 observations of 35 variables related to the performace of students in two subjects (Mathematics and Portuguese).The data attributes contain information about students grades, demographic, and social(including alcohol consumption) activities. Details of the attributes can be obtained from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance

Let’s select 4 variables that have relationship with alcohol consumption and state a hypotheses for each of them

Selecetd variables:Grade(G2),absences,studytime,and health

Hypothesis(1): with high alcohol consumption, student grade decreases

Hypothesis(2): with high alcohol consumption rate, student absence rate increases

Hypothesis(3): with high alcohol consumption rate, student study less time

Hypothesis(4): with high alcohol consumption rate, student’s health condition deteriorates more

Let’s numerically and graphically explore variable distributions and relationships with alcohol consumption

There are more female (198) students than male(184) in the survey. More female students scored the highest grade than male. The largest number of students absent(58) from the class is for 2 days.Most of the students study for 2-5 hours,i.e. 2 refers to 2-5 hour. Moreover, majority are in a very good health condition (45.11% of male and 30.81% of female)

Regarding their relationship with alcohol use, the result indicates that with high alcohol use the grades for both female and male students decreases. The decline in grade is, however, more significant for male students than female. The overall result agrees well with the hypothesis stated above

With high rate of alcohol consumption, the number of absent male students is higher than those with low consumption. Where as for female students, the rate of alcohol consumption have no effect, i.e. the median value remain the same for both high and low consumption. Therefore the hypothesis holds true only for male students

The resut showed that alcohol consumption rate has no impact on the studytime for both male and female student. Thus, the hypothesis is not true

The result show that with high alcohol consumption, female student’s health consitions shows improvement; wheras for male students, it has no effect. Hence, the hypotheis stated above is not true based on the results obtained

The result shows that absences from class and studytime have significant relationship with the probability of alcohol consumption rate, while health and grade(G2) do not. Being absent from class has a positive relationship whereas studytime has negative relation with the probality of alcohol consumption rate, i.e.a unit increase in absence increases the probability of high alcohol consumption by 0.07714, while a unit increase in study time decreases the probability of high alcohol consumption by 0.50762

The odd ratio for absences(1.0801949) tells us that absences is positively associated with alcohol consumption(value>1) whereas study time is negatively related(value<1). At 97.5% conidence interval, small values for both variables indicates that the precision of odd ratio is good. Moreover,the result agrees well with both hypothesis stated above, i.e. with high alcohol consumption, student absence increase while study time decrease

# add the predicted probabilities to 'Stud_Alc_Cons'
Stud_Alc_Cons <- mutate(Stud_Alc_Cons, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
Stud_Alc_Cons <- mutate(Stud_Alc_Cons, prediction = probability>0.5)

# calculate training error
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}


loss_func(class = Stud_Alc_Cons$high_use, prob = Stud_Alc_Cons$probability)
## [1] 0.2827225

The resut shows that the model error is 0.28, which means the model can commit a pediction error of about 28%

# performing 10-fold cross validation
library(boot)
cros_val <- cv.glm(data = Stud_Alc_Cons, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m1, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cros_val$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2905759

The prediction error is 0.28. Hence, I didn’t find a better model compared to the model in the DataCamp

The Boston data contain infromation about housing values in the suburbs of Boston, USA. There are 506 observations of 14 variables in the dataset.The variables(attributes) are:

crim- per capita crime rate by town.

zn - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

indus- proportion of non-retail business acres per town.

chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).

nox - nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).

rm - average number of rooms per dwelling.

age - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.

dis - weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.

rad - index of accessibility to radial highways.

tax - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.

ptratio- pupil-teacher ratio by town.

black -1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.

lstat -lower status of the population (percent).

medv -median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

# create a categorical variable 'crime'
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label=c("low","med_low","med_high","high"))
# Drop the old crime rate variable from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)
#Divide the dataset to train and test sets
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

All the means of the variables are standarzed to a common mean value of zero and distributed according to their difference or distance from the mean value(zero).

library(MASS)
# Fit the linear discriminant analysis on the train set
lda.fit <- lda(crime~., data = train)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# Draw the LDA (bi)plot
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2,col=classes,pch=classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crime

# remove the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)
# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       15      17        1    0
##   med_low    3      14        3    0
##   med_high   0      13       15    1
##   high       0       0        1   19

The first linear discriminant(which achieved 94.5% separability) classifies the high crime rate correclty(100%). As can be seen from the table, all 22 are correctly classified(see the blue clusters in the bi-plot). Whereas there is some level of overlap or poor prediction for medium low and medium high categories(red and green clusters in the bi-plot)

#Reload the Boston dataset and standardize the dataset
data("Boston")
scaled_data <- scale(Boston)

dist_man <- dist(Boston)
#Run k-means algorithm on the dataset
km4 <-kmeans(Boston, center=4)
km3 <-kmeans(Boston, center=3)
km2 <-kmeans(Boston, center=2)
# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston[6:10], col = km4$cluster)

pairs(Boston[6:10], col = km3$cluster)

pairs(Boston[6:10], col = km2$cluster)

#Investigate optimal number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# determine the k-means clustering and run the model again
km <-kmeans(Boston, centers = 2)

#plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

As we can see from the pairs plot, three and four clusters show significant overlap between clusters. Thus to determine the optimal number of clusters, let’s use twcss. Plots of testing using the cluters sums of squares with in each cluster(twcss) shows(with maximum number of clusters to be 10) there are two distinct clusters. The sharp change in the twcss line graphs occurs at the second cluster from very high to low. The final results of the pairs plot with two clusters(red and black) now shows very clear separation with minimal overlap compared to the previous cluster(4 and 3).
